article.description:
Chris Webber picked up the slack for an
injured Allen Iverson, scoring 31 points, grabbing 10 rebounds and
adding nine assists Sunday to lead the Sixers to a 94-91 win over the Grizzlies.
article.headline: Webber takes over for A.I., leads Sixers past Grizz
article.linkText: Webber takes over for A.I., leads Sixers past Grizz
article.story:
MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- The Philadelphia 76ers finally won a close one -- and did it without Allen Iverson. Iverson sat out the second half with a sprained right ankle, but the 76ers took the lead in the final minute and held on to beat the Memphis Grizzlies 94-91 on Sunday afternoon. Chris Webber picked up the slack, scoring 31 points, grabbing 10 rebounds and adding nine assists to lead Philadelphia, which had lost its last three games by a combined eight points. "I knew it would be a lot like the last three games we had, and we'd have to win it down the stretch," Sixers coach Maurice Cheeks said. "We had a lot of guys step up when AI went down." Iverson, the league's second-leading scorer, injured the ankle near the end of the first half and did not return. Iverson left the locker room in a walking boot under his own power. The 76ers said Iverson's X-rays were negative. He will be re-evaluated Monday. "Obviously, it's bad if I couldn't return," Iverson said. "I just had problems walking. I knew I couldn't do any running." Webber was 12-of-19 from the field and led five Sixers in double figures. Webber's 14-footer with 48 seconds left gave Philadelphia the lead for good, and the Sixers held on despite hitting only half of their 6 free throws in the final seconds. Pau Gasol's desperation shot from well beyond halfcourt for Memphis as time expired did not come close. Iverson had 18 points and six assists before leaving. Steven Hunter and Andre Iguodala each scored 13 points and reserve John Salmons had 12. "When AI goes down like that, it's really hard for all of us," Webber said. "But I wasn't surprised (that the rest of the team stepped up). That's why I wanted to pass the ball around to guys and let them do what they can do." After Hunter blocked 7-foot-2 Jake Tsakalidis' dunk attempt, and Memphis committed two turnovers, the Sixers had an 89-87 lead. "It was one of those instinctive things to do," Hunter said of the block. "(Tsakalidis) was killing us on the boards all day, and I was frustrated by that. I know he's not a great leaper, but he's tall." Gasol's tip-in with a minute left knotted the game at 89. But Webber hit the go-ahead 14-footer, and Kyle Korver and Iguodala added free throws for the final margin after Gasol scored on a dunk with 15 seconds remaining. Tsakalidis led Memphis with 17 points and 12 rebounds, while Gasol and Mike Miller scored 16 apiece. Chucky Atkins finished with 15 points. "We didn't seem to feel comfortable," Gasol said. "That was the feeling I had during the whole game. We couldn't get to our offense. We couldn't get to what we wanted out of the plays we ran. It really wasn't a consistent offense on our part. We were very sloppy." The Sixers got untracked early with Iverson and Webber leading the way. Iverson already had reached double figures and Webber had nine before the end of the opening quarter. Philadelphia also forced eight early turnovers, with Iverson stepping into the lane for steals that looked like the passes were intended for him. The Sixers led by as many as 10 in the half, but Memphis closed to 50-44 at the break as Miller scored 10. Webber had 17 in the half, to go with Iverson's 18 before the injury. On the play, Iverson drove to the right taking a shot from the right baseline as the shot clock expired. Iverson said he injured the ankle when he landed on some people sitting along the baseline after falling out of bounds. Iverson was not putting any weight on the leg when he limped to the Philadelphia bench. After the Sixers called timeout, Iverson was carried to the dressing room. Memphis opened the second half on a 26-12 run fueled by 11 points apiece in the quarter from Tsakalidis and Atkins, propelling the Grizzlies to a 70-62 lead, their biggest lead of the game. Iguodala's dunk with under a second left pulled Philadelphia within 73-70 entering the fourth.

Game notes
University of Memphis coach John Calipari visited both locker rooms prior to the game, spending time with Iverson and Grizzlies coach Mike Fratello. ... Memphis G Eddie Jones returned to action after missing three games with a nagging left foot injury. He was limited to 15 minutes and two points. Grizzlies G Bobby Jackson sat out the game with a pulled rib muscle. ... Memphis' 22 turnovers were two short of its season high. ... Webber's nine assists were a season high. ... Some of the postgame locker room banter involved the NCAA brackets announced while the teams were playing. Memphis G Dahntay Jones, a Duke grad, was already crowing about the Blue Devils' chances, while Webber was mumbling about Michigan being snubbed.
